<section class="section section--alt" id="qb-help-sales-tax-issues-definition">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">In plain terms</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">&ldquo;Sales tax issues,&rdquo; plainly.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>QuickBooks tracks the sales tax you charge customers and totals what you owe each taxing agency on a liability report. When people say they have &ldquo;sales tax issues,&rdquo; they usually mean one of a few things: the <em>wrong rate</em> is being charged on invoices; the sales-tax <em>liability or return doesn&rsquo;t match</em> what the books say you collected; tax is set to a single <em>flat rate</em> instead of the correct combined rate for the customer&rsquo;s jurisdiction; items are marked <em>taxable when they&rsquo;re exempt</em> (or the reverse); or QuickBooks Online&rsquo;s <em>Automated Sales Tax</em> is calculating off an address or product tax category that needs correcting.</p>
      <p>The good news is that most of these trace to a short list of causes, and the self-fix steps below address them in order of likelihood &mdash; correcting the setup and item taxability clears a large share of cases. What the steps <em>can&rsquo;t</em> do is determine taxability law or file your return. We configure and reconcile sales tax inside QuickBooks so the liability is accurate and ties to the books; the actual rates and the rules for what&rsquo;s taxable are set by each state and jurisdiction, and the return itself is filed by your CPA or directly with the state. And if the underlying issue is your Intuit account or an Intuit-side Automated Sales Tax outage, that&rsquo;s Intuit&rsquo;s to resolve &mdash; not something we can reach.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

